      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "CFD solver must be under version control with documented test suite; all simulation scripts archived with checksums.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (OpenFOAM v8) is maintained under Git version control with a documented regression test suite covering 47 canonical cases. Simulation scripts and boundary condition files are archived with SHA-256 checksums. Achieved level meets required level for Low assurance at MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Order-of-accuracy tests must confirm spatial discretization convergence rate within 10% of theoretical order for representative benchmark cases.",
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions applied to the rotating frame Navier-Stokes equations confirms second-order spatial convergence (observed rate 1.93) on three systematically refined grids. Temporal convergence verified separately. Achieved level meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Richardson extrapolation-based GCI must be computed on at least three grid levels; GCI for hemolysis index must be below 8% at the operating point of maximum hemolysis.",
      "rationale": "Grid convergence study performed on coarse (4.2 M cells), medium (11.7 M cells), and fine (31.4 M cells) meshes. Richardson extrapolation yields GCI of 5.3% for the hemolysis index at the worst-case operating point (6 L/min, 3500 RPM). Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, rotational speed, fluid viscosity, hematocrit) must be reproduced in simulation within stated measurement uncertainty bands.",
      "rationale": "All five FDA benchmark operating points reproduced with inlet flow rates within ±0.05 L/min and rotational speeds within ±5 RPM of measured values. Fluid rheology matched to published viscosity data for porcine blood at 37 °C and 40% hematocrit. Test conditions adequately replicated."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted hemolysis index (HI) must agree with experimental measurements within two experimental standard deviations across all five operating points; pressure rise must agree within 5%.",
      "rationale": "Predicted HI falls within two experimental standard deviations at 4 of 5 operating points; the fifth point (3 L/min, 2500 RPM) falls within 2.3 standard deviations, attributed to low-flow recirculation sensitivity. Pressure rise predictions within 3.8% across all points. Achieved level 3 meets required level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The hemolysis index computed from the power-law damage accumulation model must be directly comparable to the clinical hemolysis metric used in device acceptance.",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) derived from the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model is the same metric used in ISO 10993-4 and FDA guidance for VAD hemolysis acceptance. Direct correspondence confirmed. Quantity of interest is fully relevant to the COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments must use the same FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, the same blood analog or blood, and operating conditions spanning the VAD clinical envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation data drawn from the FDA benchmark dataset using the identical generic centrifugal pump CAD geometry. Porcine blood experiments span 3–6 L/min and 2500–3500 RPM, encompassing the clinical VAD operating envelope. Validation activities are directly relevant to the COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated by residual reduction of at least four orders of magnitude and monitored hemolysis index must stabilize within 0.5% over the final 500 iterations.",
      "rationale": "All five steady-state simulations achieve residual reductions exceeding five orders of magnitude. Hemolysis index monitor shows variation below 0.2% over the final 500 iterations for all operating points. Numerical solver error is well controlled at achieved level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup must be independently reviewed by a second analyst; boundary condition and material property inputs must be documented in a traceable simulation log.",
      "rationale": "An independent CFD analyst reviewed the complete simulation setup including mesh, boundary conditions, turbulence model selection, and hemolysis model coefficients. All inputs documented in a traceable simulation log with version-controlled parameter files. Use error controlled at achieved level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The choice of turbulence closure (SST k-omega) and hemolysis damage accumulation model must be justified against published benchmark comparisons for rotary blood pump applications.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega turbulence closure selected based on published comparative studies for rotary blood pumps showing superior near-wall shear stress prediction relative to standard k-epsilon. Power-law hemolysis model coefficients from Giersiepen et al. (1990) with Lagrangian particle tracking. Model form justified at level 3 through literature and benchmark evidence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Uncertainty in key model inputs (viscosity, hematocrit, power-law exponents) must be propagated via Monte Carlo analysis with at least 500 samples; resulting uncertainty bounds on HI must be reported.",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo UQ performed with 1000 samples propagating uncertainty in dynamic viscosity (±8%), hematocrit (±3%), and power-law damage exponents (±15% per published variability). 95th-percentile HI uncertainty band reported as ±22% of nominal prediction. Input uncertainty characterization meets level 3 requirements."
    },
    {
